<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-vectors-3d">
 <title>1.2 Vectors in Three Dimensions</title>
<p>
    In order to represent points in space, we first choose a fixed point <m>O</m> (the origin) and 
    three directed lines through <m>O</m> which are perpendicular to each other, called the 
    <term>coordinate axes</term>. They are labeled as the <term><m>x</m>-axis</term>, <term><m>y</m>-axis</term>, 
    and <term><m>z</m>-axis</term>. Think of the <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-axes as being horizontal while the 
    <m>z</m>-axis is vertical. The direction of the <m>z</m>-axis is determined by the <term>right-hand rule</term>.
</p>

<p>
    The three coordinate axes determine the three <term>coordinate planes</term>. 
    The <m>xy</m>-plane contains the <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-axes, the <m>yz</m>-plane contains the <m>y</m>- 
    and <m>z</m>-axes, and the <m>xz</m>-plane contains the <m>x</m>- and <m>z</m>-axes. 
    These three coordinate planes divide space into eight parts, called <term>octants</term>. 
    The <term>first octant</term> is determined by the positive axes.
</p>

<p>
    We represent a point <m>P</m> by the ordered triple <m>(a,b,c)</m> of real numbers and we call <m>a</m>,
     <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> the <term>coordinates</term> of <m>P</m>; here, <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>
      are the <m>x</m>-, <m>y</m>-, and <m>z</m>-coordinates, respectively. </p>
<p> 
    The point <m>P(a,b,c)</m> can be visualized as a corner of a rectangular box. 
    If we drop a perpendicular from <m>P</m> to the <m>xy</m>-plane, we get a point <m>Q</m> with 
    coordinates <m>(a,b,0)</m> called the <term>projection</term> of <m>P</m> on the <m>xy</m>-plane.
</p>

<p>
    The Cartesian product <m>\mathbb{R} \times \mathbb{R} \times \mathbb{R} = \{(x,y,z) \mid x,y,z \in \mathbb{R}\}</m> 
    is the set of all ordered triples of real numbers and is denoted by <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-surfaces-in-3d">
    <statement>
        <p>
            What surfaces in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> are represented by the following equations?
        </p>
        <ol marker="1">
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>z=3</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>y=5</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <ol marker="1">
            <li>
                <p>
                    The equation <m>z=3</m> represents the set of all points <m>\{(x,y,z) \mid z=3\}</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>. Since <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> can be any real numbers, this forms a horizontal plane parallel to the <m>xy</m>-plane, located exactly <m>3</m> units above it.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-plane-z3">
                    <caption>The plane <m>z=3</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.</caption>
                    <image xml:id="img-plane-z3" width="50%">
                        <shortdescription>A 3D coordinate system showing a shaded blue horizontal plane intersecting the vertical z-axis at the value 3.</shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[>=stealth, scale=0.8]
                                % Axes
                                \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (-2,-2) node[left] {$x$};
                                \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (4,0) node[right] {$y$};
                                \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (0,4) node[above] {$z$};
                                
                                % Axis ticks
                                \draw (0,2.5) -- (0.1,2.5) node[right] {\footnotesize $3$};
                                
                                % Shaded plane z=3
                                \filldraw[fill=blue!20, draw=blue, opacity=0.6] (-1.5,1) -- (2.5,1) -- (1,4) -- (-3,4) -- cycle;
                                \node[blue] at (1.5,3.5) {$z=3$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The equation <m>y=5</m> represents the set of all points <m>\{(x,y,z) \mid y=5\}</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>. Since <m>x</m> and <m>z</m> can be any real numbers, this forms a vertical plane parallel to the <m>xz</m>-plane, located exactly <m>5</m> units to the right of it.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-plane-y5">
                    <caption>The plane <m>y=5</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.</caption>
                    <image xml:id="img-plane-y5" width="50%">
                        <shortdescription>A 3D coordinate system showing a shaded red vertical plane intersecting the horizontal y-axis at the value 5.</shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[>=stealth, scale=0.8]
                                % Axes
                                \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (-2,-2) node[left] {$x$};
                                \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (4,0) node[right] {$y$};
                                \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (0,4) node[above] {$z$};
                                
                                % Axis ticks
                                \draw (3,0) -- (3,0.1) node[above] {\footnotesize $5$};
                                
                                % Shaded plane y=5
                                \filldraw[fill=red!20, draw=red, opacity=0.6] (3,-1) -- (3,3) -- (1,1) -- (1,-3) -- cycle;
                                \node[red] at (2.8,2) {$y=5$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </solution>
</example>

<fact xml:id="fact-distance-formula-3d">
    <title>Distance Formula in Three Dimensions</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            The distance <m>d(P_1, P_2) = |P_1P_2|</m> between the points <m>P_1(x_1,y_1,z_1)</m> and <m>P_2(x_2,y_2,z_2)</m> is:
            <me>d(P_1, P_2) = |P_1P_2| = \sqrt{(x_2-x_1)^2 + (y_2-y_1)^2 + (z_2-z_1)^2}</me>
        </p>
    </statement>
</fact>

<example xml:id="ex-distance-3d">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Find the distance from the point <m>P(-1,-3,1)</m> to the point <m>Q(3,4,-2)</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            Substitute the coordinates of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> into the three-dimensional distance formula:
            <md>
                <mrow>|PQ| \amp = \sqrt{(3 - (-1))^2 + (4 - (-3))^2 + (-2 - 1)^2}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{(3 + 1)^2 + (4 + 3)^2 + (-3)^2}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{4^2 + 7^2 + (-3)^2}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{16 + 49 + 9}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{74}</mrow>
            </md>
            The exact distance between the points is <m>\sqrt{74}</m>.
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<fact xml:id="fact-equation-of-sphere">
    <title>Equation of a Sphere</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            An equation of a sphere with center <m>C(h,k,l)</m> and radius <m>r</m> is:
            <me>(x-h)^2 + (y-k)^2 + (z-l)^2 = r^2</me>
            If the center is at the origin <m>O(0,0,0)</m>, then the equation of the sphere simplifies to:
            <me>x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = r^2</me>
        </p>
    </statement>
</fact>

<example xml:id="ex-sphere-completing-square">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Show that <m>x^2+y^2+z^2+4x-6y+2z+6=0</m> is the equation of a sphere, and find its center and radius.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            To transform the given equation into standard form, group the variables and complete the square for each variable:
            <md>
                <mrow>(x^2 + 4x) + (y^2 - 6y) + (z^2 + 2z) \amp = -6</mrow>
                <mrow>\left(x^2 + 4x + \left(\frac{4}{2}\right)^2\right) + \left(y^2 - 6y + \left(\frac{-6}{2}\right)^2\right) + \left(z^2 + 2z + \left(\frac{2}{2}\right)^2\right) \amp = -6 + 4 + 9 + 1</mrow>
                <mrow>(x^2 + 4x + 4) + (y^2 - 6y + 9) + (z^2 + 2z + 1) \amp = 8</mrow>
                <mrow>(x + 2)^2 + (y - 3)^2 + (z + 1)^2 \amp = 8</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Comparing this result to the standard equation of a sphere <m>(x-h)^2 + (y-k)^2 + (z-l)^2 = r^2</m>, we find:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The center of the sphere is <m>C(h,k,l) = C(-2, 3, -1)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The radius is <m>r = \sqrt{8} = 2\sqrt{2}</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-region-spherical-shell">
    <statement>
        <p>
            What region in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> is represented by the following inequalities?
            <me>1 \leq x^2+y^2+z^2 \leq 4</me>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            The expression <m>x^2+y^2+z^2 = r^2</m> represents the squared distance from the origin to a point in three-dimensional space. We can rewrite the inequality by taking the square root of all parts:
            <me>1 \leq \sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2} \leq 2</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            This represents the set of all points whose distance <m>r</m> from the origin satisfies <m>1 \leq r \leq 2</m>. Therefore, the region is a solid <term>spherical shell</term> (or a thick hollow sphere) centered at the origin, including the inner sphere of radius <m>1</m> and the outer sphere of radius <m>2</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-spherical-shell">
            <caption>The spherical shell bounded by <m>r = 1</m> and <m>r = 2</m>.</caption>
            <image xml:id="img-spherical-shell" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>A 3D rendering of a small inner sphere enclosed within a larger, semi-transparent outer sphere layer centered at the origin.</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[>=stealth, scale=1.2]
                        % Draw coordinate axes
                        \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (-1.5,-1.5) node[left] {$x$};
                        \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (3,0) node[right] {$y$};
                        \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (0,3) node[above] {$z$};
                        
                        % Outer sphere back layer
                        \draw[blue!40, dashed] (0,0) ellipse (2cm and 0.6cm);
                        
                        % Inner sphere solid / dashed layers
                        \fill[gray!20] (0,0) circle (1cm);
                        \draw[thick, gray] (0,0) circle (1cm);
                        \draw[gray, dashed] (0,0) ellipse (1cm and 0.3cm);
                        
                        % Outer sphere front shaded layer
                        \filldraw[fill=blue!10, draw=blue, opacity=0.5] (0,0) circle (2cm);
                        \draw[blue] (0,0) ellipse (2cm and 0.6cm);
                        
                        % Radius indicator lines
                        \draw[->, thick, black] (0,0) -- (0.707,0.707) node[midway, left] {\footnotesize $1$};
                        \draw[->, thick, black] (0,0) -- (-1.2,1.6) node[midway, right] {\footnotesize $2$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-region-solid-cylinder">
    <statement>
        <p>
            What region in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> is represented by the following inequalities?
            <me>x^2+y^2 \leq 25, \quad |z| \leq 3</me>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            We analyze the two conditions independently to find their intersection:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In the <m>xy</m>-plane, <m>x^2+y^2 \leq 25</m> describes a solid disk of radius <m>5</m> centered at the origin. Since <m>z</m> is unconstrained by this expression, it forms an infinitely long solid cylinder extending along the <m>z</m>-axis.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The absolute value inequality <m>|z| \leq 3</m> is equivalent to <m>-3 \leq z \leq 3</m>. This bounds the space vertically between two horizontal planes.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            Combining these conditions restricts the infinite cylinder to a specific height. Therefore, the region is a <term>solid vertical cylinder</term> of radius <m>5</m> and height <m>6</m>, centered along the <m>z</m>-axis and extending from <m>z = -3</m> to <m>z = 3</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-solid-cylinder">
            <caption>The solid vertical cylinder bounded by <m>x^2+y^2 \leq 25</m> and <m>-3 \leq z \leq 3</m>.</caption>
            <image xml:id="img-solid-cylinder" width="55%">
                <shortdescription>A 3D coordinate system containing a shaded vertical cylinder centered along the vertical axis. The flat top cap sits at z equals 3, and the flat bottom cap sits at z equals negative 3.</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[>=stealth, scale=0.5]
                        % Lower background elements 
                        \draw[red!40, dashed] (0,-3) ellipse (3cm and 0.9cm);
                        
                        % Shaded cylinder body side profile
                        \fill[red!10, opacity=0.6] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
                        \fill[red!10, opacity=0.6] (0,3) ellipse (3cm and 0.9cm);
                        \fill[red!5, opacity=0.4] (0,-3) ellipse (3cm and 0.9cm);
                        
                        % Draw Main Coordinate Axes 
                        \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (-2.5,-2.5) node[left] {$x$};
                        \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$y$};
                        \draw[->, thick] (0,-4.5) -- (0,5) node[above] {$z$};
                        
                        % Outlining cylinder boundaries
                        \draw[thick, red] (-3,-3) -- (-3,3);
                        \draw[thick, red] (3,-3) -- (3,3);
                        \draw[thick, red] (0,3) ellipse (3cm and 0.9cm);
                        \draw[thick, red] (-3,-3) arc (180:360:3cm and 0.9cm);
                        
                        % Label structural values on axes (UPDATED: Clean tracking positions)
                \draw (0,3) -- (0.1,3) node[below right] {\footnotesize $z=3$};
                \draw (0,-3) -- (0.1,-3) node[right] {\footnotesize $z=-3$};
                \draw[black, ->] (0,3) -- (2.5,2.5) node[above right] {\footnotesize $r=5$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </solution>
</example>

<fact xml:id="fact-vector-operations-3d">
    <title>Vector Operations in Three Dimensions</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>\vec{a} = \langle a_1,a_2,a_3 \rangle</m> and <m>\vec{b} = \langle b_1,b_2,b_3 \rangle</m> be vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
        </p>
        <ol marker="1">
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Addition of vectors</term>: 
                    <me>\vec{a}+\vec{b} = \langle a_1+b_1, a_2+b_2, a_3+b_3 \rangle</me>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Scalar multiple of a vector</term>: 
                    <me>c\vec{a} = c\langle a_1,a_2,a_3 \rangle = \langle ca_1, ca_2, ca_3 \rangle</me>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The <term>zero vector 0</term>: 
                    <me>\vec{0} = \langle 0,0,0 \rangle</me>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The <term>negative -a</term> of a vector <m>\vec{a}</m>: 
                    <me>-\vec{a} = -\langle a_1,a_2,a_3 \rangle = \langle -a_1, -a_2, -a_3 \rangle</me>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The <term>difference a-b</term>: 
                    <me>\vec{a}-\vec{b} = \vec{a}+(-\vec{b}) = \langle a_1-b_1, a_2-b_2, a_3-b_3 \rangle</me>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The length of <m>\vec{a} = \langle a_1,a_2,a_3 \rangle</m>: 
                    <me>\|\vec{a}\| = \sqrt{a_1^2+a_2^2+a_3^2}</me>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If <m>P_1(x_1,y_1,z_1)</m> and <m>P_2(x_2,y_2,z_2)</m> are any points, the vector <m>\vec{a}</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> that corresponds to <m>\vec{P_1P_2}</m> is: 
                    <me>\vec{a} = \langle x_2-x_1, y_2-y_1, z_2-z_1 \rangle</me>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </statement>
</fact>

<definition xml:id="def-standard-basis-3d">
    <statement>
        <p>
            The <term>standard basis vectors</term> in three dimensions are:
            <me>\vec{i} = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle, \quad \vec{j} = \langle 0,1,0 \rangle, \quad \vec{k} = \langle 0,0,1 \rangle</me>
            If <m>\vec{a} = \langle a_1,a_2,a_3 \rangle</m>, then it can be written as a linear combination of the standard unit basis vectors:
            <me>\vec{a} = a_1\vec{i} + a_2\vec{j} + a_3\vec{k}</me>
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="ex-linear-combination-3d">
    <statement>
        <p>
            If <m>\vec{a} = \vec{i} + 2\vec{j} - 3\vec{k}</m> and <m>\vec{b} = 4\vec{i} + 7\vec{k}</m>, express the vector <m>2\vec{a} + 3\vec{b}</m> in terms of <m>\vec{i}</m>, <m>\vec{j}</m>, and <m>\vec{k}</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            Substitute the given expressions for <m>\vec{a}</m> and <m>\vec{b}</m>, distribute the scalars, and group the components:
            <md>
                <mrow>2\vec{a} + 3\vec{b} \amp = 2(\vec{i} + 2\vec{j} - 3\vec{k}) + 3(4\vec{i} + 0\vec{j} + 7\vec{k})</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = (2\vec{i} + 4\vec{j} - 6\vec{k}) + (12\vec{i} + 0\vec{j} + 21\vec{k})</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = (2 + 12)\vec{i} + (4 + 0)\vec{j} + (-6 + 21)\vec{k}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = 14\vec{i} + 4\vec{j} + 15\vec{k}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-unit-vector-3d">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Find the unit vector in the direction of the vector <m>\vec{v} = 2\vec{i} - \vec{j} - 2\vec{k}</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            First, find the magnitude of the given vector <m>\vec{v}</m>:
            <me>\|\vec{v}\| = \sqrt{2^2 + (-1)^2 + (-2)^2} = \sqrt{4 + 1 + 4} = \sqrt{9} = 3</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Next, multiply the reciprocal of the magnitude by the vector <m>\vec{v}</m> to produce the unit vector <m>\vec{u}</m>:
            <me>\vec{u} = \frac{1}{3}(2\vec{i} - \vec{j} - 2\vec{k}) = \frac{2}{3}\vec{i} - \frac{1}{3}\vec{j} - \frac{2}{3}\vec{k}</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-wire-tension-static">
    <statement>
        <p>
            A 100-lb weight hangs from two wires making angles of <m>50^\circ</m> and <m>32^\circ</m> with the horizontal. Find the tensions (forces) <m>\vec{T}_1</m> and <m>\vec{T}_2</m> in both wires and their magnitudes.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            We express the tension vectors in terms of their horizontal and vertical components. Let <m>\vec{T}_1</m> pull up and to the left, and <m>\vec{T}_2</m> pull up and to the right:
            <md>
                <mrow>\vec{T}_1 \amp = -\|\vec{T}_1\|\cos(50^\circ)\vec{i} + \|\vec{T}_1\|\sin(50^\circ)\vec{j}</mrow>
                <mrow>\vec{T}_2 \amp = \|\vec{T}_2\|\cos(32^\circ)\vec{i} + \|\vec{T}_2\|\sin(32^\circ)\vec{j}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            The downward force due to the weight is <m>\vec{w} = -100\vec{j}</m>. For the system to achieve static equilibrium, the resultant sum of the tensions must exactly counterbalance the weight:
            <me>\vec{T}_1 + \vec{T}_2 = -\vec{w} = 100\vec{j}</me>
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-wire-tension-vectors">
            <caption>Force vector diagram for the hanging weight system.</caption>
            <image xml:id="img-wire-tension-vectors" width="55%">
                <shortdescription>A free body vector diagram showing a central point from which three arrows emerge: one pointing down labeled w equals 100 lb, one pulling up and left at 50 degrees labeled T1, and one pulling up and right at 32 degrees labeled T2.</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[>=stealth, scale=1.3]
                        % Reference horizontal baseline
                        \draw[dashed, thick, gray!60] (-2.5,0) -- (3.5,0);
                        
                        % Central anchor point
                        \filldraw (0,0) circle (2.5pt);
                        
                        % Weight vector w pointing down
                        \draw[->, ultra thick, black] (0,0) -- (0,-2) node[below] {$\vec{w} = -100\vec{j}$};
                        
                        % Tension 1 pulling left and up (50 degrees)
                        % 180 - 50 = 130 degrees
                        \draw[->, ultra thick, blue] (0,0) -- (130:2.5) node[above left] {$\vec{T}_1$};
                        \draw[thick, blue] (-0.5,0) arc (180:130:0.5);
                        \node[blue, above left] at (-0.4,0.05) {\footnotesize $50^\circ$};
                        
                        % Tension 2 pulling right and up (32 degrees)
                        \draw[->, ultra thick, red] (0,0) -- (32:3.2) node[above right] {$\vec{T}_2$};
                        \draw[thick, red] (0.6,0) arc (0:32:0.6);
                        \node[red, right] at (0.5,0.15) {\footnotesize $32^\circ$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
            Equating the horizontal (<m>\vec{i}</m>) and vertical (<m>\vec{j}</m>) components gives a system of linear equations:
            <md>
                <mrow>-\|\vec{T}_1\|\cos(50^\circ) + \|\vec{T}_2\|\cos(32^\circ) \amp = 0</mrow>
                <mrow>\|\vec{T}_1\|\sin(50^\circ) + \|\vec{T}_2\|\sin(32^\circ) \amp = 100</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            From the first equation, we find <m>\|\vec{T}_2\| = \|\vec{T}_1\|\frac{\cos(50^\circ)}{\cos(32^\circ)}</m>. Substituting this relationship into the second equation yields:
            <me>\|\vec{T}_1\|\sin(50^\circ) + \|\vec{T}_1\|\frac{\cos(50^\circ)\sin(32^\circ)}{\cos(32^\circ)} = 100</me>
            <me>\|\vec{T}_1\|\left(\sin(50^\circ) + \cos(50^\circ)\tan(32^\circ)\right) = 100</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Solving for the magnitudes yields:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\|\vec{T}_1\| \approx 85.64\text{ lb}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\|\vec{T}_2\| = 85.64 \cdot \frac{\cos(50^\circ)}{\cos(32^\circ)} \approx 64.91\text{ lb}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            Substituting these scalar magnitudes back into our component formulas provides the final tension vector models:
            <me>\vec{T}_1 \approx -55.05\vec{i} + 65.60\vec{j}</me>
            <me>\vec{T}_2 \approx 55.05\vec{i} + 34.40\vec{j}</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

</section>